PN,35310
SC,0010
PS,c000
OL,0,        ECIMSBWebfax     F353A1672876098
OL,6,FThey argue mobile services in current
OL,7,FTV spectrum will help them improve 5G
OL,8,Fservices and coverage and pave the way
OL,9,Ffor future services, perhaps 6G.
OL,11,FVirgin Media O2 sees the remaining TV
OL,12,Ffrequencies as a way of covering "deep
OL,13,Frural areas". It's broadly an argument
OL,14,Fcopied and pasted from a decade ago,
OL,15,Fbut with 4G replaced by 5G.
OL,17,FBut as mobile users will know, 4G and
OL,18,F5G services still have many coverage
OL,19,Fgaps. Some networks aren't fully using
OL,20,Fthe ex-TV frequencies they've already
OL,21,Fgot hold of.
OL,3,CCampaign to save terrestrial TV hits a
OL,4,Csnag
OL,1,W~+$ hw1~{4~k4 ~shw1~sj7}  S    G10/14
OL,2,W+.!+,"-$/*%/*% / "-$+,*-'U(,,,,,,,,,,,,
PN,35311
SC,0011
PS,c000
OL,0,        ECIMSBWebfax     F353A1672876098
OL,6,FTo recap: the mobile operators now
OL,7,Foperate on 700 and 800 MHz bands
OL,8,F(mobile bands 20 and 28). Up for grabs
OL,9,Fin ITU Region 1 are the sub-700 MHz
OL,10,Ffrequencies still used for TV.
OL,12,FThe lower the frequency the less suited
OL,13,Fthey are to deliver fast internet,
OL,14,Funless a single mobile operator can
OL,15,Fsecure a wide slice of spectrum in any
OL,16,Fauction.
OL,18,FThe low frequencies are primarily
OL,19,Fbeneficial for ensuring a mobile has a
OL,20,Fsignal and can do basic tasks.
OL,3,CCampaign to save terrestrial TV hits a
OL,4,Csnag
OL,1,W~+$ hw1~{4~k4 ~shw1~sj7}  S    G11/14
OL,2,W+.!+,"-$/*%/*% / "-$+,*-'U(,,,,,,,,,,,,
PN,35312
SC,0012
PS,c000
OL,0,        ECIMSBWebfax     F353A1672876098
OL,6,FThat's why there's also a push by the
OL,7,Fmobile networks to utilise other,
OL,8,Fhigher frequencies, that can offer ever
OL,9,Ffaster speeds, but have smaller
OL,10,Fcoverage areas.
OL,12,FIn the USA (ITU region 2), the 600 MHz
OL,13,Ffrequency band is already used for
OL,14,Fmobile. Arguably, this helps operators
OL,15,Freach remote parts of the country,
OL,16,Fareas where you can travel by car for
OL,17,Fhours with little change in the
OL,18,Fscenery.
OL,3,CCampaign to save terrestrial TV hits a
OL,4,Csnag
OL,1,W~+$ hw1~{4~k4 ~shw1~sj7}  S    G12/14
OL,2,W+.!+,"-$/*%/*% / "-$+,*-'U(,,,,,,,,,,,,
PN,35313
SC,0013
PS,c000
OL,0,        ECIMSBWebfax     F353A1672876098
OL,6,FThat's deeper than the deep rural areas
OL,7,Fof the UK Virgin Media O2 refers to.
OL,8,FBut even they are dependent on higher
OL,9,Ffrequencies to actually deliver the
OL,10,Fspeeds expected of 5G. Here, they are
OL,11,Fusing mmWave (above 24 GHz), at the
OL,12,Fopposite end of the spectrum from
OL,13,Fterrestrial TV.
OL,15,FmmWave can deliver large quantities of
OL,16,Fcapacity in places like transport hubs
OL,17,Fand stadia where you might find a high
OL,18,Fnumber of users in a small space,
OL,19,Fexactly what the current TV frequencies
OL,20,Faren't very good at doing.
OL,3,CCampaign to save terrestrial TV hits a
OL,4,Csnag
OL,1,W~+$ hw1~{4~k4 ~shw1~sj7}  S    G13/14
